1
00:00:02,478 --> 00:00:27,861
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa

2
00:00:28,414 --> 00:00:32,762
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:34,363 --> 00:00:45,081
So on this full moon, by the way, I hope you saw the blood moon for the full moon itself on the clear sky.

4
00:00:45,240 --> 00:00:49,968
It wasn't actually the full moon, but it was very red.

5
00:00:49,987 --> 00:00:52,252
I don't know whether you all caught that.

6
00:00:52,371 --> 00:00:53,173
It was very lovely.

7
00:00:56,090 --> 00:01:01,718
So the topic I've chosen for this one is dukkha and sila.

8
00:01:03,039 --> 00:01:07,826
So these are words that I'm sure you're familiar with, but it's good to have a little reminder.

9
00:01:09,248 --> 00:01:15,177
Dukkha translated as unsatisfactoriness, as suffering.

10
00:01:15,310 --> 00:01:44,084
simply means hard to bear but you know why does it manifest so it manifests because of three basic roots these unwholesome roots the delusion which forks off into some form of acquisitiveness and some form of aversion and the aversion spikes off into hatred and fear so these are our basic attitudes that we

11
00:01:44,064 --> 00:01:47,188
that arise out of this deep delusion.

12
00:01:49,090 --> 00:02:06,950
So, in order to go backwards to the original delusion, we have to work through the moral laws and ethical guidance.

13
00:02:07,808 --> 00:02:11,294
The moral laws, I'm just using these words to mean two different things.

14
00:02:11,334 --> 00:02:14,117
The moral laws are basically things like, you know, not to kill.

15
00:02:14,718 --> 00:02:21,310
But the ethical guidance is really about relationships, about changing our relationship.

16
00:02:21,330 --> 00:02:28,602
And, you know, not only to people, animals, plants, but even to material things.

17
00:02:28,986 --> 00:02:43,091
So, for instance, at Hieiji Monastery, the founding monastery of Zen, I'm told that when they take water from a well, they will use the water but always leave a little bit to put back into the well.

18
00:02:43,853 --> 00:02:48,159
It's a sort of offering, it's a sort of acknowledgement of the preciousness of water.

19
00:02:50,062 --> 00:02:54,570
Now the thing about this suffering, remember, is that we cause it to ourselves.

20
00:02:54,651 --> 00:03:01,643
And what's difficult for us to really accept is that we actually are doing it since we were born.

21
00:03:01,943 --> 00:03:04,747
In fact, we're probably doing it in the womb.

22
00:03:05,182 --> 00:03:24,127
And you have to make this distinction between the pressures coming upon us, even as babies, which are usually not meant to be harmful, such as the process of birth, feeling hungry and mummy's not there.

23
00:03:24,146 --> 00:03:30,955
And of course, there are acts against us which can be harmful.

24
00:03:31,356 --> 00:03:55,491
whatever happens to us is shall we say the original pain how we react to it through aversion etc is our suffering and you have to we have to recognize that if that were not so it would be impossible to become fully liberated unless we got rid of the

25
00:03:55,859 --> 00:04:15,842
the actual cause of our suffering if we believe other people are the cause of our suffering then basically we've got to get rid of other people and then we can be liberated but it's the very fact that we cause our own suffering that we can become fully liberated from it

26
00:04:17,915 --> 00:04:29,333
Now, I just want to just remind you of things, but I really want to center upon what they're known as the defilements and the latent tendencies, but we'll come to that in a minute.

27
00:04:29,353 --> 00:04:41,391
So the five basic laws are places that I'm sure none of us go there, but it's good to know that there is, you know, things that we don't do anymore, like kill people.

28
00:04:41,370 --> 00:05:06,112
we don't kill anybody if we can and we don't steal we don't tell lies we don't abuse our sexual powers the last one's a bit difficult not to take drugs and drink and all that sort of stuff which make the mind fuzzy we do live in an alcohol culture but it's up to the individual but i think

29
00:05:06,093 --> 00:05:23,291
If one brings to mind that alcohol, no matter how little it is, is actual pure poison to the body, probably worse than any of the drugs, then that might go for non-alcoholic wine and beers, which I can tell you now are very good

30
00:05:26,949 --> 00:05:36,845
So the one about telling, what happens is of course that when we take those precepts, obviously we move towards the opposite.

31
00:05:36,865 --> 00:05:42,975
So we don't kill anybody, but kill any being or anything like that.

32
00:05:42,995 --> 00:05:46,218
And we just naturally move towards protecting them.

33
00:05:46,720 --> 00:05:49,004
It's just a natural movement towards that.

34
00:05:50,165 --> 00:05:53,110
Sometimes that first precept is,

35
00:05:53,899 --> 00:06:22,000
translated as no harm but it's not it's actually killing right so it's actually a refinement if you're not harming any living being not to steal when we give that up of course we know that that leads to a harmonious society and eventually generosity sexual powers is of course the use of those is is out of respect and within a loving relationship

36
00:06:22,603 --> 00:06:29,740
Now, when it comes to lying, of course, right speech, it splits into four different types.

37
00:06:29,841 --> 00:06:35,093
I mean, there are great big whoppers that we don't want to tell anymore, but slandering is a bit more difficult.

38
00:06:35,113 --> 00:06:37,017
We will let words slip.

39
00:06:38,264 --> 00:06:58,685
find ourselves saying things about people and then there's abusive language of course and just wasted talk you know just talking for talking sake and what we're moving towards is kindly speech truthful beneficial and most of

40
00:06:58,665 --> 00:07:09,088
importance to speak to say things at a suitable time because often we're saying what we what we want to say, but it's not quite the right time to say it.

41
00:07:13,838 --> 00:07:15,122
And we have this other

42
00:07:15,675 --> 00:07:31,086
category of hindrances where all these things come up as hindrances to our meditation when we're sitting so they it's just another another sort of list which allows us to see where these defilements within us are

43
00:07:31,504 --> 00:07:33,086
and how to deal with them.

44
00:07:33,127 --> 00:07:35,230
Each category has a way of dealing with them.

45
00:07:35,290 --> 00:07:36,291
I'm sure you remember.

46
00:07:36,732 --> 00:07:43,182
So the first one being all to do with sensual desires, avarice, greed, and all that sort of stuff.

47
00:07:43,341 --> 00:07:50,031
The next one is all the hatreds, the grudges, the vendettas, and then the...

48
00:07:53,355 --> 00:07:55,959
I've just moved a bit, just a minute.

49
00:07:56,446 --> 00:08:09,500
Yeah, and then there's this sloth and torpor, which is, you know, it comes about through our habit of using sleep to escape, to get rid of ourselves for a little while.

50
00:08:09,521 --> 00:08:11,663
I think somebody called the duvet dive.

51
00:08:12,144 --> 00:08:18,011
So when you do that, of course, you're developing an energy which is pulling you down.

52
00:08:18,031 --> 00:08:19,833
It's like a whirlpool, you know.

53
00:08:20,533 --> 00:08:25,980
So these things have to be overcome, have to be allowed to drain themselves.

54
00:08:26,737 --> 00:08:33,989
And then there's that whole area of restlessness caused by just inner turbulence.

55
00:08:34,529 --> 00:08:45,807
But that also contains guilt, remorse and shame, which are secondary effects of doing something harmful.

56
00:08:47,121 --> 00:08:54,149
And then finally, skeptical doubt, which is quite a problem if you have it badly because you can't make a decision.

57
00:08:54,629 --> 00:09:00,236
You keep sort of making lists for and against.

58
00:09:00,297 --> 00:09:04,421
If you have a relationship where you might, yes, you are attracted.

59
00:09:04,500 --> 00:09:05,022
Could it work?

60
00:09:05,062 --> 00:09:05,802
Could it not work?

61
00:09:05,903 --> 00:09:07,524
Before you know it, the person's left you.

62
00:09:08,166 --> 00:09:09,187
It's the same with a job.

63
00:09:09,586 --> 00:09:10,347
Shall I go for it?

64
00:09:10,368 --> 00:09:11,349
Shall I not go for it?

65
00:09:11,369 --> 00:09:12,149
And he's gone.

66
00:09:13,057 --> 00:09:19,227
So it often comes from fear of failure or a lack of self-esteem or something like that.

67
00:09:21,311 --> 00:09:26,619
Anyway, just moving on to the kilesa.

68
00:09:26,639 --> 00:09:30,384
So this is often translated as the ten defilements.

69
00:09:30,445 --> 00:09:35,352
Now, in the early scriptures, the word kilesa is used as a sort of general term.

70
00:09:35,772 --> 00:10:03,653
way of pointing to that within us which is unwholesome but of course later on it's very the early scriptures can't resist and the Abidama couldn't resist in making lists so they've given us a list of ten of these defilements and none of them will come as a shock I mean you know they're there but

71
00:10:04,054 --> 00:10:09,982
The reason for looking at this is in order to, for self-reflection.

72
00:10:10,323 --> 00:10:18,895
So that when we see thoughts coming up, when we see our actions coming up, then it sort of categorizes it and it gives us some idea of how to deal with it.

73
00:10:20,097 --> 00:10:27,548
So the first one obviously is to do with sensual desire, basic sensual desire, you know, the greed, the lust, the avarice and so on.

74
00:10:29,418 --> 00:10:31,980
The next one is to do with hatred, with hate.

75
00:10:32,041 --> 00:10:35,605
So it's unforgivingness and things like that, you know, holding grudges.

76
00:10:37,288 --> 00:10:38,629
The next one is delusion.

77
00:10:39,211 --> 00:10:44,057
And this is always around this fundamental problem of identity.

78
00:10:44,378 --> 00:10:49,965
It's always about this feeling of being a self, a person, something that doesn't change within us.

79
00:10:51,147 --> 00:10:59,037
And this, of course, then gives us this moving from this self, which is actually only seeking happiness.

80
00:10:59,320 --> 00:11:23,352
it's only seeking happiness then it gives us some sort of purpose for life to seek this happiness but unfortunately as we know human life doesn't eventually satisfy us you know it's not it's not somewhere where we're ever going to feel completely satisfied and this also manifests as conceit so uh conceit has three

81
00:11:23,873 --> 00:11:36,769
manifestations of course the the obvious one is you know i'm i am better than i'm better than you etc and then you get the opposite of you know i'm i'm not as good as right

82
00:11:37,306 --> 00:11:42,138
And then you get a more subtle one where you sort of feel that this is okay.

83
00:11:42,337 --> 00:11:44,503
I'm equal to, I'm equal to this person.

84
00:11:44,523 --> 00:11:48,412
So there doesn't seem to be any conceit of I'm better or worse.

85
00:11:49,335 --> 00:11:52,682
You know, that seems to be, that seems to be a good place to be.

86
00:11:52,783 --> 00:11:55,769
It's sort of wholesome, but unfortunately,

87
00:11:56,357 --> 00:12:01,349
You are creating a group of people who all think that they are equal.

88
00:12:01,708 --> 00:12:09,144
Now once you've done that, there are other groups which are not equal and they are actually worse or better.

89
00:12:09,645 --> 00:12:12,392
So it's a subtle one that.

90
00:12:14,903 --> 00:12:16,849
The next one is wrong views.

91
00:12:17,169 --> 00:12:21,101
And this really goes back again to the self.

92
00:12:21,884 --> 00:12:29,486
And it's about believing that something of our personhood is eternal.

93
00:12:30,091 --> 00:12:37,841
I mean, we all know the body will die, but the heart-mind, the mental body continues to live, never changes.

94
00:12:38,701 --> 00:12:51,879
The soul, often people will talk about their souls as being this unchanging person, basically, but without a physical body.

95
00:12:52,315 --> 00:12:54,837
And that, of course, is not the Buddha's teaching.

96
00:12:54,918 --> 00:13:01,004
The subtle body, the body that seeks rebirth, is just as impermanent as this one.

97
00:13:01,365 --> 00:13:06,270
It is just a more finer energy.

98
00:13:06,711 --> 00:13:10,936
Now, when I say that, sometimes you can experience that.

99
00:13:12,317 --> 00:13:19,065
When you're there with an emotion, something loud, like you might be feeling irritated,

100
00:13:19,484 --> 00:13:21,707
or anxious is a bit difficult.

101
00:13:21,808 --> 00:13:24,553
Irritation or anger, that's a good one.

102
00:13:25,054 --> 00:13:29,043
And you're in the body and you can feel it.

103
00:13:29,062 --> 00:13:29,684
You can feel it.

104
00:13:31,086 --> 00:13:32,429
You might be able,

105
00:13:33,018 --> 00:13:54,638
you know by centering in on it very clearly by holding your attention right there it might just separate for you and then you'll see that the mind's anger isn't that bad but that when it touches the physical base of the body it's like a sounding box it comes back as very loud as very burning

106
00:13:55,394 --> 00:14:04,924
And little experiences like that prove to the meditator that these two things, the body and mind, are actually two different forms of energy.

107
00:14:05,466 --> 00:14:07,989
But neither of them are permanent.

108
00:14:08,408 --> 00:14:10,010
They're arising and passing away.

109
00:14:11,812 --> 00:14:15,738
And the opposite of eternalism, of course, is annihilationism.

110
00:14:16,899 --> 00:14:21,163
Like the idea that when you die, well, you're dead and that's it.

111
00:14:21,304 --> 00:14:22,566
So you should be happy with that.

112
00:14:23,153 --> 00:14:44,924
now um in the buddhist time there were materialists they were people who believed that um there wasn't a soul there wasn't anything it was you know you were just this body and that when you died you died so these days we would have scientific materialists who would take that position and uh

113
00:14:45,158 --> 00:14:47,822
Definitely the Buddha was against both, right?

114
00:14:48,202 --> 00:14:57,937
And he tended to be accused of being an annihilationist, not an eternalist, because of his teaching of not-self.

115
00:14:57,956 --> 00:15:00,600
And it became very confusing, this not-self business.

116
00:15:01,162 --> 00:15:11,216
And the James said, we believe, ourselves and the Brahmins, we believe that there is an eternal soul.

117
00:15:11,482 --> 00:15:14,385
And the materialists believe that there isn't.

118
00:15:14,926 --> 00:15:20,631
But the Buddhists haven't made their mind up.

119
00:15:21,873 --> 00:15:26,638
That was how confused people were with this doctrine of not-self.

120
00:15:27,519 --> 00:15:30,542
And there are occasions in the scriptures which are quite funny, actually.

121
00:15:31,182 --> 00:15:34,586
We'll do that some other time.

122
00:15:34,806 --> 00:15:37,489
Then we've got this skeptical doubt, which we've talked about.

123
00:15:38,149 --> 00:15:40,831
And torpor, again, which we've talked about.

124
00:15:41,149 --> 00:15:42,171
and restlessness.

125
00:15:42,772 --> 00:15:54,505
So those are your 10 Kilesa, sensual desire, hatred, delusion, conceit, wrong view, skeptical doubt, torpor and restlessness.

126
00:15:55,006 --> 00:15:58,831
What I'm going to do is just put these lists onto a PDF if you want to have a look.

127
00:15:59,591 --> 00:16:02,655
But there's lots of stuff on the websites.

128
00:16:03,576 --> 00:16:07,782
If you want to go into a bit more deeply,

129
00:16:08,419 --> 00:16:17,693
But the next bit is particularly interesting, I think, for us as Westerners, is this idea of anusaya, which are latent tendencies.

130
00:16:18,075 --> 00:16:23,943
So this tells you that within us there are these habits, sankara.

131
00:16:24,345 --> 00:16:31,034
So sankara is often translated as volitional conditioning, which is really confusing.

132
00:16:31,386 --> 00:16:36,316
But if we think about habits, it's just what we habitually do.

133
00:16:36,515 --> 00:16:42,847
All that, the way we think, the way we speak, our thought patterns, these are all habits.

134
00:16:42,927 --> 00:16:49,480
And the compendium of habits is what we would call our personality, character.

135
00:16:49,914 --> 00:16:55,341
it's understood that these are lying underneath everything we're doing.

136
00:16:55,923 --> 00:17:06,174
And given an opportunity, given some sort of catalyst, some sort of stimulus, there will arise out of this sankara a response.

137
00:17:06,736 --> 00:17:19,332
So for instance, all of us have some amount of anger within us, and if somebody stands on your foot, then that's a little stimulus, and this angle will want to sort of reply to it.

138
00:17:19,970 --> 00:17:22,712
And it's lying there dormant, okay?

139
00:17:22,732 --> 00:17:23,875
It's lying there dormant.

140
00:17:24,655 --> 00:17:39,953
And what the Buddha is saying is that these are actually underneath our obvious consciousness, but that they're always ready and they're always, in many ways, affecting the present moment.

141
00:17:39,973 --> 00:17:48,744
So it's translated as bent bias, proclivity, all those sorts of words.

142
00:17:51,137 --> 00:17:53,560
They're exactly the same.

143
00:17:53,641 --> 00:18:06,896
The list is much the same as the defilements, of course, with one extra one, or one different one, which is the tendency of the desire to become.

144
00:18:07,317 --> 00:18:09,019
In other words, that will to live.

145
00:18:09,579 --> 00:18:12,083
And its opposite, the will not to live.

146
00:18:12,501 --> 00:18:23,696
So this will to live will lead us to beliefs of eternalism and the desire not to live will lead us to beliefs about annihilationism.

147
00:18:24,438 --> 00:18:34,451
And obviously, if you have that desire to live, then you'll do everything to keep alive and you will substantiate your life.

148
00:18:34,491 --> 00:18:39,719
You'll try to make it safer and safer with more money, more friends, etc., etc.

149
00:18:39,739 --> 00:18:41,682
It causes us to be acquisitive.

150
00:18:42,099 --> 00:19:01,819
If you are on the other side, where there's a sort of feeling of okay with annihilation, with the fact that death is the end of it and all that, then you'll find such people often taking refuge in sleep, the duvet dive.

151
00:19:01,900 --> 00:19:06,825
As soon as something's too much, well, you just lie down and go to sleep.

152
00:19:07,582 --> 00:19:14,570
But of course, on its worst level, it's suicide, just wanting to get rid of yourself.

153
00:19:14,590 --> 00:19:17,434
Unfortunately, in Buddhist understanding, that doesn't work.

154
00:19:17,755 --> 00:19:18,816
It will re-arise.

155
00:19:20,038 --> 00:19:23,742
So it's not a good solution.

156
00:19:25,845 --> 00:19:30,230
So that tendency there is put in as an underlying tendency.

157
00:19:30,328 --> 00:19:35,355
which is making us grasp everything which proves to us that we're alive.

158
00:19:35,976 --> 00:19:43,463
And that means trying to make ourselves happy, defending what makes ourselves happy from any enemies.

159
00:19:43,825 --> 00:19:44,986
So there's your aversion.

160
00:19:45,426 --> 00:19:48,230
And if the enemy is too big, well, you run for it.

161
00:19:48,770 --> 00:19:57,500
So we're constantly trying to manipulate our lives in order to establish this constant state of living happily.

162
00:19:58,932 --> 00:20:09,847
Now the last thing that I just want to mention is of course that it's translated as tendencies.

163
00:20:10,729 --> 00:20:17,358
So obviously these days we're very much aware of our prejudices and there are two words that people are using.

164
00:20:17,398 --> 00:20:24,269
They use, I mean the commentators, they use the word prejudice which is a hard sort of word.

165
00:20:25,170 --> 00:20:27,353
There's almost an activity there.

166
00:20:27,755 --> 00:20:36,833
You know, if you're racially prejudiced or sexually prejudiced and somebody calls you that, there's a sort of feeling of you being actively so.

167
00:20:37,454 --> 00:20:44,147
So the other word that's being used is bias, which is slightly softer on a person.

168
00:20:44,208 --> 00:20:49,137
But I think that if we use these two words in the sense of the

169
00:20:49,894 --> 00:21:01,534
defilements and the latent tendencies, then it allows us to accept that all these prejudices are within us.

170
00:21:01,954 --> 00:21:06,682
It's part of the baggage that we get when we are born into a culture.

171
00:21:07,223 --> 00:21:10,249
And I've got a list here of well-known prejudices.

172
00:21:12,253 --> 00:21:37,164
so there's racism obviously and tribalism which is a solid lesser form sexism ageism i'm very much against that classicism uh classic classism homophobia nationalism religious prejudice and xenophobia and and that's only a short list there's lots and lots of other prejudices so um

173
00:21:37,667 --> 00:21:40,311
It's being kind to ourselves.

174
00:21:40,332 --> 00:21:45,278
It's recognizing that we will have these prejudices within us.

175
00:21:47,021 --> 00:21:51,848
And they can manifest and sometimes it can be embarrassing for us.

176
00:21:52,710 --> 00:21:55,473
But how do we overcome?

177
00:21:56,077 --> 00:21:57,220
these prejudices.

178
00:21:57,240 --> 00:22:01,866
Well, obviously, on the obvious side, you don't indulge them.

179
00:22:01,886 --> 00:22:22,440
But the other thing that the Buddha often talks about is this yoni-so-manasi-kara, this sort of wise attention, this being really awake, that in any situation you are aware of unwholesome thoughts as they arise, not after they've arisen and done something, but as they arise.

180
00:22:22,690 --> 00:22:31,441
And when we are awake enough to actually catch these little unwholesome thoughts coming up, they very quickly dissipate.

181
00:22:31,921 --> 00:22:46,038
And in that way, these prejudices, these biases begin to be exhausted of their energy and they lose that power to take us by surprise.

182
00:22:48,842 --> 00:22:49,643
Now,

183
00:22:50,332 --> 00:22:58,426
I think one of the difficulties is that it's very difficult for us to say to ourselves, well, I am racially prejudiced.

184
00:22:59,068 --> 00:23:04,659
Well, to say that and to mean it as an active thing, of course, wouldn't be correct.

185
00:23:05,260 --> 00:23:10,230
But to say that there is in me that still, that sankara, that conditioning,

186
00:23:11,205 --> 00:23:38,192
and to be aware should it ever arise and not to indulge it i think that's a more truthful way of being with these uh conditionings within us and um it's also i think uh how should we say comforting to know that every person in the world will have these prejudices right doesn't matter what uh ethnic group you come from what race you belong to whatever

187
00:23:38,914 --> 00:23:47,347
These are just basic prejudices that are completely universal, doesn't matter where you live.

188
00:23:49,551 --> 00:23:54,599
So that allows us, I think, to be more open about ourselves, at least to ourselves anyway.

189
00:23:55,320 --> 00:24:04,315
And that means that we will be aware of these things when they arise, and they don't sneak out as Freudian slips, which can be very embarrassing.

190
00:24:07,567 --> 00:24:22,281
So what we've done this evening is just revise these moral precepts and begun to look at much more this idea of relationship.

191
00:24:22,301 --> 00:24:24,183
And we've looked at the more negative side.

